Seen at night. Thanks to Dennis Haines on bugguide for the identification and the details. Two similar species - Prionus californicus and Prionus lecontei. Differentiated based on whether the antenae show 12 or 13 segments. In P. californicus segments 12-13 are fused into one. "Prionus adults emerge from midsummer into fall, move about nocturnally and drawn to light, may fly into windows at night, crashing violently. Among the largest of the long-horned beetles, Prionus adults may be over 2 inches long with grubs growing over 4 inches long. Prionus califonicus range from Central California to Alaska and east into the great basin states and Eastern Washington." (from www.bentler.us )

description:
After an hour of research, and pot of strong coffee, I finally identified these amorous bugs as"bagrada bugs" which are native to eastern and southern Africa and parts of southern Europe and Asia. They are an introduced species in California and Arizona, where they were was first reported in 2008. They're a pest, targeting kale, radish, cabbage and turnips. The adult bug is typically shield-shaped, 5 to 7 mm long and 3 to 4 mm broad at its widest area. The upper surface has a mixture of black, white and orange markings, which gives the insect its common names harlequin bug or painted bug. 
The life cycle lasts 3 to 4 weeks and several generations may occur in a year. (Source: www.infonet-biovision.org)

description: Cypripedium californicum. This was the reason I was driving up Caribou Rd. As I was puttering along, I saw a giant wall of serpentine looming ahead, and figured I had to stop and check it out. As I pulled up, I noticed a stream, flowing along the base of the outcropping, and thought to myself, "Serpentine + water = awesome orchids." Checked it out, and sure enough, hidden among the lilies was a little patch of California lady's slippers. They were a little past prime, but I was pretty proud of my sleuthing. The ones shown above were actually further down the road, along with the stream orchids.

description: Calochortus nudus. Not too many mariposa lilies up there! This was one of the few I saw, along the road running through the Silver Lake campground.

Streptanthus tortuosus var. tortuosus. This was my first time seeing this variety, so of course I thought it was a species I hadn't seen and I was super excited. Quite common in the rocky areas surrounding Silver Lake.

This tiny piperia was all over the place in the wooded areas of Butterfly Valley.  My flash ran out of batteries as I was trying to shoot this, so I didn't really get the desired sharpness.  Still a pretty plant.

One of my guides described purple fawn lilies (Erythronium purpurescens) as blooming right after snow melt, and indeed, most of the ones I found on the short hike to Gold Lake were done for, but I manage to find one nice patch in bloom. The next day when I hiked up to the ridge, I saw lots more poking through the snow, just as described. The flowers turn purple-pink as they senesce.

description: I am always happy to find myco-heterotrophs, and this one of the first cool plants of the morning: leafless wintergreen. But when I got home and tried looking it up in CalFlora, the closest thing I could find was Pyrola picta, which... has leaves. Well, usually. Apparently there's a longstanding debate about whether leafless wintergreens are their own species or extreme variants of P. picta or P. asarifolia. Well, I say if it's debateable, I can choose my favorite name, and since there are obviously no leaves and plants that steal their food instead of making it themsleves or obviously way cooler, I'm calling it P. aphylla.
